Incorrect. The Bitcoin protocol was a mashup of hashcash + secp2k1 ECDSA + a networking protocol. Subsequent blockchains readily swap out these components for alternative consensus or signature rules while still aggregating transaction data into blocks.
Blockchains can have permissions architectures. See Tendermint, ErisDB, and Multichain as main examples of where this functionality exists.
